    {
      "action": "journal-upsert",
      "id": "v41-cohort",
      "strategy_id": "v41-cohort",
      "cohort_label": "v41",
      "hypothesis": "v41 cohort - holder_count threshold sweep on the v25-bot-excl-climbing universe. All 5 mirrors share v25 base (TP=100/SL=30, entry@T+60, 5s poll, no trailing TP, filters: top5<=30 + dd>-25 + vel<200 + age>=60 + climbing_t30_t45=1). Each adds ONE holder_count filter at thresholds 15, 16, 17, 18, 19. KNOWN DATA QUALITY CAVEAT: holder_count is capped at 19 by getTokenLargestAccounts (step 1 in collector/holder-enrichment.ts:170) and the getProgramAccounts upgrade (step 2 ~line 254) is blocked by the current RPC provider, so 100% of the dataset has holder_count <= 19. Across 1,437 loser rows in loss-postmortem.json, the buckets are: <10 = 4.3%, 10-14 = 2.4%, 15-19 = 93.2%, >=20 = 0%. Therefore: (a) >=15 excludes only the bottom ~6.7% of trades (the genuinely thin-holder tokens), (b) >=19 keeps only tokens that HIT the cap (i.e., have at least 19 unique non-infrastructure holders in the top-20 RPC slice). The progressive sweep tests whether thin-holder tokens are systematically lower-quality entries, and where the threshold starts hurting volume more than it helps quality. Expected volume curve: >=15 nearly matches v25, dropping monotonically to >=19 which keeps ~93% of v25's universe.",
      "prediction": {
        "target_net_sol": 0,
        "target_n": 100,
        "target_days": 21,
        "kill_criterion": "cohort-level - see individual variants"
      },
      "status": "OPEN"
    },
